{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17604061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17604061"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T12:47:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T12:47:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15793"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15793"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.81,0.05,0,0.1,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8484"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62605"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8484"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15793"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48052"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"8684"},{"type":"tags","id":"10556"},{"type":"tags","id":"10557"},{"type":"tags","id":"10559"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20391"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20392"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62605","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62605"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring spermiogenesis (the final stage of spermatogenesis), haploid spermatids undergo several structural modifications to become mature spermatozoa.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following changes occurs during the differentiation of spermatids into spermatozoa?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Formation of acrosome","Decondensation of nucleus","Reduction in mitochondrial number","Shortening of flagellum","Retention of cytoplasm"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring spermiogenesis, several key structural modifications occur:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eformation of acrosome\u003C/strong\u003E from the Golgi apparatus creates a specialised vesicle containing enzymes necessary for egg penetration\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ERather than \u003Cstrong\u003Edecondensation of nucleus\u003C/strong\u003E, there is actually intense nuclear condensation where histones are replaced by protamines\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EInstead of \u003Cstrong\u003Ereduction in mitochondrial number\u003C/strong\u003E, mitochondria are reorganised and concentrated in the midpiece\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ERather than \u003Cstrong\u003Eshortening of flagellum\u003C/strong\u003E, there is elongation and development of the tail structure\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EInstead of \u003Cstrong\u003Eretention of cytoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E, there is significant reduction in cytoplasmic volume to create a streamlined cell\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese changes create a highly specialised cell capable of delivering genetic material to the egg.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Spermiogenesis involves nuclear condensation, not decondensation","Key changes in spermiogenesis include acrosome formation, nuclear condensation, mitochondrial reorganisation, tail development, and cytoplasmic reduction"],"references":["O\u0027Donnell L, Nicholls PK, O\u0027Bryan MK, McLachlan RI, Stanton PG. Spermiation: The process of sperm release. Spermatogenesis. 2011 Jan;1(1):14-35. doi: 10.4161/spmg.1.1.14525. PMID: 21866274; PMCID: PMC3158646.","Griswold MD. Spermatogenesis: The Commitment to Meiosis. Physiol Rev. 2016 Jan;96(1):1-17. doi: 10.1152/physrev.00013.2015. P